University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Eyton (Shrops) or Eaton (Cheshire, Leics, Staffs), or Eaton Bray (Beds), Cold Eaton or Long Eaton (Derbys)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ayton","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from Ayton (North Yorkshire) or Ayton (Berwickshire). The former is derived from Old Norse <i>á</i> ‘river, stream’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead’. The later takes its name from the River Eye (likely from Old English <i>ēa</i> ‘river, stream’) + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":62,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When George Eyton was born about 1393, in Thorndon, Suffolk, England, his father, George Eyton, was 16 and his mother, Lady Jane Brereton, was 24. He married Elizabeth de Thorndon in 1416, in Thorndon, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. He was buried in Thorndon, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"abt 1393–":"umbes 1393–Surnud","1393–Male":"1393–Surnud","1395–1448":"1395–1448","1397–1470":"1397–1470","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1397–Female":"1397–Surnud","1399–1419":"1399–1419","1419–1476":"1419–1476","1379–1476":"1379–1476","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1396":"1396","abt 1393":"umbes 1393","1395":"1395","1470":"1470","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","Abt 1417":"umbes 1417","1448":"1448","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1399":"1399","1453":"1453","1397":"1397","1419":"1419","1416":"1416","1405":"1405","Thorndon, Suffolk, England":"Thorndon, Suffolk, England","Thorndon Manor; Pershore, Suffolk, England":"Thorndon, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","Ickworth, Suffolk, England":"Ickworth, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thorndon, Mid Suffolk District, Suffolk, England":"Thorndon, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abt 1393–":"noin 1393–Kuollut","1393–Male":"1393–Kuollut","1395–1448":"1395–1448","1397–1470":"1397–1470","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1397–Female":"1397–Kuollut","1399–1419":"1399–1419","1419–1476":"1419–1476","1379–1476":"1379–1476","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1396":"1396","abt 1393":"noin 1393","1395":"1395","1470":"1470","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","Abt 1417":"noin 1417","1448":"1448","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1399":"1399","1453